  sodium: 1330 mg
---

Wash and dry produce.

Thinly slice @tomato{1} into rounds. Halve @potato bun{2}.

Heat a large dry, preferably #nonstick pan{} over medium-high heat. Add @bacon{4%oz}; cook, turning occasionally and adjusting heat if browning too quickly, until crispy, ~{6-10%minutes}. Turn off heat; transfer bacon to a #paper-towel-lined plate{}. Wipe out pan.

In a #medium bowl{}, combine @ground beef{10%oz} and @fajita spice blend{1%tbsp}.

Form beef mixture into two equal-size balls (four balls for 4 servings); season all over with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a large, preferably nonstick pan over medium-high heat. Add beef and flatten each ball with a #spatula{} to create very thin patties. Cook to desired doneness, ~{3-4%minutes} per side. (Don't worry if the patties aren't perfectly round—those irregular edges will turn crispy.)

In the last ~{1-2%minutes} of cooking, top patties with @Mexican cheese blend{1/2%cup} and cover pan to melt cheese.

> Use pan used for bacon here.

While patties cook, toast buns until golden brown.

Spread top buns with @guacamole{4%tbsp} and @hot sauce{1%tsp} to taste.

Place patties, bacon, tomato, and a few @blue corn tortilla chips{1.5%oz} on bottom buns. Close buns.

Divide burgers between plates. Serve with remaining tortilla chips on the side.

> Place patties, bacon, tomato, and a few tortilla chips on bottom buns.

> Bacon is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.

> Ground Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.